SIMPLE: pattern
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pattern
<hw>Pat"tern</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>patron</ets>, F. <ets>patron</ets>, a patron, also, a pattern. See
<er>Patron</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Anything proposed for
imitation; an archetype; an exemplar; that which is to be, or is worthy
to be, copied or imitated; <as>as, a <ex>pattern</ex> of a
machine</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will be the <qex>pattern</qex> of all patience.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A part showing the figure or quality of the whole; a
specimen; a sample; an example; an instance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He compares the <qex>pattern</qex> with the whole piece.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Stuff sufficient for a garment; <as>as, a dress
<ex>pattern</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Figure or style of decoration; design; <as>as, wall
paper of a beautiful <ex>pattern</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Something made after a model; a copy.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>patterns</qex> of things in the heavens.</q>
<rj><qau>Heb. ix. 23.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Anything cut or formed to serve as a guide to
cutting or forming objects; <as>as, a dressmaker's
<ex>pattern</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Founding)</fld> <def>A full-sized model around
which a mold of sand is made, to receive the melted metal. It is usually
made of wood and in several parts, so as to be removed from the mold
without injuring it.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>a recognizable characteristic relationship or set of
relationships between the members of any set of objects or actions, or
the properties of the members; also, the set having a definable
relationship between its members.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><note> Various collections of objects or markings are spoken of as a
<ex>pattern</ex>. Thus: the distribution of bomb or shell impacts on a
target area, or of bullet holes in a target; a set of traits or actions
that appear to be consistent throughout the members of a group or over
time within a group, as behavioral <ex>pattern</ex>, traffic
<ex>pattern</ex>, dress <ex>pattern</ex>; the wave <ex>pattern</ex> for
a spoken word; the <ex>pattern</ex> of intensities in a spectrum; a
grammatical <ex>pattern</ex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <fld>(Gun.)</fld> <def>A diagram showing the distribution
of the pellets of a shotgun on a vertical target perpendicular to the
plane of fire.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>the recommended flight path for an airplane to
follow as it approaches an airport for a landing. Same as
<altname>landing pattern</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <def>an image or diagram containing lines, usually
horizontal, vertical, and diagonal, sometimes of varying widths, used to
test the resolution of an optical instrument or the accuracy of
reproduction of image copying or transmission equipment. Same as
<altname>test pattern</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>pattern box</b></col>, <col><b>pattern
chain</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>pattern cylinder</b></col></mcol>
<fld>(Figure Weaving)</fld>, <cd>devices, in a loom, for presenting
several shuttles to the picker in the proper succession for forming the
figure.</cd> -- <col><b>Pattern card</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>A set
of samples on a card</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Weaving)</fld> <cd>One of
the perforated cards in a Jacquard apparatus.</cd> -- <col><b>Pattern
reader</b></col>, <cd>one who arranges textile patterns.</cd> --
<col><b>Pattern wheel</b></col> <fld>(Horology)</fld>, <cd>a
count-wheel.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pattern</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Pattern
<hw>Pat"tern</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Patterned</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Patterning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make or design
(anything) by, from, or after, something that serves as a pattern; to
copy; to model; to imitate.</def> <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[A temple] <qex>patterned</qex> from that which Adam reared in
Paradise.</q> <rj><qau>Sir T. Herbert.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To serve as an example for; also, to
parallel.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To pattern after</b></col>, <cd>to imitate; to
follow.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>patterned</ent>⟦br⟧
